			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">MMC3 has <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/MMC3" class="postlink">reference documents</a> produced by the reverse engineers of the greater NESdev community. If you have programmed for any other non-trivial mapper, these reference documents should help you get a status bar working.<br /><br />If that's too long:<br /><ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Make sure the background is using the first pattern table ($0000) and the sprites the second ($1000). </li><li>Disable all other IRQ sources (APU frame, APU DMC) and set the interrupt priority to 0 with <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">cli</tt>. (Priority 0 lets IRQ and NMI through; priority 1 lets only NMI through.) </li><li>In your NMI handler, make any necessary updates to OAM, palette, and video memory (in that order), scroll the playfield into view, write the number of scanlines above your status bar to $C000 (PIT period), then write anything to $C001 (reload PIT) and $E001 (enable PIT IRQ). </li><li>In your IRQ handler, write anything to $E000 (disable PIT IRQ) and scroll the status bar into view. </li></ol></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

