						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Tsutarja wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Getting closer. I managed to get rid of the flickering by disabling/enabling rendering in NMI instead of the subroutines that may require it. It also makes my NMI code slightly more faster when there is a lot of graphical updates.</div><br />Actually, you don't have to disable and re-enable rendering at all, as long as all the updates fit inside VBlank time (which they should!). If you can't guarantee that, turning rendering off and back on will prevent VRAM corruption, but the screen will &quot;jump&quot;.</div>

