			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Tsutarja wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">the IRQ begin generated will set X scrolling to #$FF (which seems to be the beginning of the second nametable when mirroring vertically)</div><br />it's actually the very end of the first name table (1 pixel of it) followed by 255 pixels of the second name table. It might not make much of a difference, but the correct way to show all 256 pixels of the second name table would be to set the X scroll to 0 ($2005) and select the second name table using PPUCTRL ($2000).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">and then store #$00 to Y scrolling</div><br />The vertical scroll can't be set mid-frame using $2005. Whatever value you try to write will not have any effect. To affect the vertical scroll in any way, you need to write to $2006 in addition to $2005. Values written to $2006 affect the scroll in a different way. Here's how the 16-bit value written to $2006 is interpreted by the NES:<br /><br />1st byte: *yyyNNYY<br />2nd byte: YYYXXXXX<br /><br />XXXXX: coarse X scroll;<br />YYYYY: coarse Y scroll;<br />NN: name table;<br />yyy: fine Y scroll;<br /><br />It would be possible to set the scroll to any position you wanted using only $2006, except for 2 little problems: 1- the fine X scroll can only be set through $2005; 2- when you write the second byte, the PPU automatically clears the highest y bit from the first write, so you lose some control over the fine Y scroll. These problems can be solved by mixing $2005 and $2006 writes together, but most NES programmers back in the time didn't know that. In any case, status bars always start at an even tile boundary, meaning that the fine Y scroll is always 0, so this isn't an issue in this case.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

